### Tool Class — `WeatherTools.cs`

```csharp
using System.ComponentModel;
using System.Text.Json;
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;

[McpServerToolType]
public class WeatherTools(HttpClient httpClient, ILogger<WeatherTools> logger)
{
    [McpServerTool, Description("Get current weather for a city.")]
    public async Task<string> GetWeather(
        [Description("City name, e.g. 'London'")] string city,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Fetching weather for {City}", city);
        var response = await httpClient.GetStringAsync(
            $"https://api.weatherapi.com/v1/current.json?q={city}",
            cancellationToken);
        return response;
    }

    [McpServerTool, Description("Get 3-day weather forecast for a city.")]
    public async Task<string> GetForecast(
        [Description("City name")] string city,
        [Description("Number of days (1-3)")] int days = 3,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        var response = await httpClient.GetStringAsync(
            $"https://api.weatherapi.com/v1/forecast.json?q={city}&days={days}",
            cancellationToken);
        return response;
    }
}
```

### `Program.cs` — stdio transport

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;

var builder = Host.CreateApplicationBuilder(args);

// CRITICAL: log to stderr only — stdout is the JSON-RPC transport
builder.Logging.AddConsole(options =>
    options.LogToStandardErrorThreshold = LogLevel.Trace);

builder.Services.AddHttpClient();  // registers IHttpClientFactory + HttpClient

builder.Services.AddMcpServer()
    .WithStdioServerTransport()
    .WithToolsFromAssembly();      // discovers all [McpServerToolType] classes

await builder.Build().RunAsync();
```

---

### How DI works for MCP tools

The SDK supports **two injection styles**:

1. **Constructor injection (non-static class, shown above)** — The class is instantiated per-request. Services like `HttpClient` and `ILogger<T>` are injected via the primary constructor. Register them in `Program.cs` (`AddHttpClient()`, etc.).

2. **Method parameter injection (static class)** — DI services appear directly as method parameters:
   ```csharp
   [McpServerToolType]
   public static class Tools
   {
       [McpServerTool, Description("...")]
       public static async Task<string> Fetch(
           [Description("ID")] string id,
           HttpClient httpClient,          // injected by DI, hidden from schema
           CancellationToken ct = default) // also hidden from schema
       { ... }
   }
   ```

**Key rule:** The SDK automatically distinguishes DI services (`HttpClient`, `ILogger<T>`, `CancellationToken`, `IMcpServer`, `IProgress<>`) from tool parameters. Only parameters with `[Description]` appear in the tool's JSON schema that the LLM sees. Everything else is injected silently.
